SIMPLE: nominate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nominate
<hw>Nom"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Nominated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Nominating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>nominatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>nominare</ets> to nominate, fr.
<ets>nomen</ets> name. See <er>Name</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mention by name; to name.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>nominate</qex> them all, it is impossible.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To call; to entitle; to denominate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To set down in express terms; to state.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is it so <qex>nominated</qex> in the bond?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To name, or designate by name, for an office or
place; to appoint; esp., to name as a candidate for an election, choice,
or appointment; to propose by name, or offer the name of, as a candidate
for an office or place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nominately</ent>⟦br⟧
